PBS

```json
{
  "application": "PBS",
  "details": {
    "job_name": "runAnimation-<TMPL_VAR NAME=iJob>",
    "user": "<TMPL_VAR NAME=linuxUser>:<TMPL_VAR NAME=linuxUser>",
    "email": "<TMPL_VAR NAME=emailAddress>",
    "walltime": "1:00:00",
    "nodes": "1:ppn=1",
    "memory": "1300mb",
    "virtual_memory": "5gb",
    "output_log": "<TMPL_VAR NAME=outDir>/<TMPL_VAR NAME=conditionSetTimeStamp>/<TMPL_VAR NAME=movieSubFolder>/out.animation-<TMPL_VAR NAME=iJob>.log",
    "error_log": "<TMPL_VAR NAME=outDir>/<TMPL_VAR NAME=conditionSetTimeStamp>/<TMPL_VAR NAME=movieSubFolder>/err.animation-<TMPL_VAR NAME=iJob>.log",
    "umask": "002",
    "matlab_prefdir": "/tmp/emptydir",
    "mcr_cache_root": "/tmp/mcr_cache_$PBS_JOBID",
    "xapplresdir": "/usr/local/bin/MATLAB/MATLAB_Compiler_Runtime/v716/X11/app-defaults",
    "ld_library_path": "$LD_LIBRARY_PATH:/usr/local/bin/MATLAB/MATLAB_Compiler_Runtime/v716/runtime/glnxa64:/usr/local/bin/MATLAB/MATLAB_Compiler_Runtime/v716/sys/os/glnxa64:/usr/local/bin/MATLAB/MATLAB_Compiler_Runtime/v716/sys/java/jre/glnxa64/jre/lib/amd64/native_threads:/usr/local/bin/MATLAB/MATLAB_Compiler_Runtime/v716/sys/java/jre/glnxa64/jre/lib/amd64/server:/usr/local/bin/MATLAB/MATLAB_Compiler_Runtime/v716/sys/java/jre/glnxa64/jre/lib/amd64",
    "base_dir": "<TMPL_VAR NAME=baseDir>",
    "path_to_runtime": "<TMPL_VAR NAME=pathToRunTime>",
    "out_dir": "<TMPL_VAR NAME=outDir>",
    "condition_set_timestamp": "<TMPL_VAR NAME=conditionSetTimeStamp>",
    "movie_sub_folder": "<TMPL_VAR NAME=movieSubFolder>",
    "n_frame_render_jobs": "<TMPL_VAR NAME=nFrameRenderJobs>",
    "afterany": "<TMPL_VAR NAME=afterany>"
  }
}
```

This script is designed to run within the PBS (Portable Batch System) environment. The script utilizes various PBS directives to define job parameters, resources, dependencies, and notification settings. It appears to be running a MATLAB animation script, leveraging MATLAB Compiler Runtime for execution. The script includes commands to setup the environment variables, manage the MCR cache directory, and execute the animation process using a `run.sh` script.  Additional features include dependency management for job execution, logging and error handling, and cleanup operations.  The script makes use of variables defined within a template system (likely using a tool like Jinja2 or similar).  It's worth noting that the specific behavior of the script heavily relies on the content of the `run.sh` script and the  MATLAB code.
